betterquesting:10.desc:8:
If you are totally new to Modded Minecraft, congratulations on opening this book! Let's learn how to use it.

As part of each quest in this book, you must complete one or more tasks, of which there are several possible types. The First, and simplest, is the Checkbox Task. To complete this task, all you have to do is check the box. The Second, and most common, is the retrieval task. For this, you must have a certain number of a certain item or set of items in your inventory, and you must have them all at once. Let's try it out with six wooden logs. This type of task may require you to submit the items, when it says "Consume: Yes" at the top. Collect some more logs and submit them to try it out.

There is also the crafting task, which requires you to have crafted a certain number of items. Make some planks to try it out.

Congratulations, you now know the basics of the quest book! For completing all four tasks in this quest, you may have some food and torches. Click the "Claim" button below to claim your reward!

In this modpack, we have two very important quality of life mods: Just Enough Items and The One Probe.
Just Enough Items is an item and recipe viewing mod. It is responsible for the item menu on the right side of your inventory. JEI’s features are achieved with keybinds. 
Pressing R will allow you to see all recipes for a specific item. Many items have multiple recipes, but some only have one. In the top right corner of some recipes you may see a small shuffle icon, this means the recipe is Shapeless and the items can be placed anywhere in the Crafting Grid. In the bottom right side of the recipe, you will see a + icon. Clicking it will, if you have the items in your inventory, move the items into the crafting grid for you for one recipe. Shift-clicking it will do the same but move the most items it can to make the most crafting recipes it can. If you don’t have the items in your inventory, it will tell what items you are currently missing.
Pressing U will allow you to find all uses for a specific item, as an example, if you hit U on an iron ingot, you will see the recipe for an Iron sword, chestplate, etc.

The One Probe is a UI improvement mod that adds block information directly into the game for you, with an unobtrusive tooltip on the top of your screen. TOP will display information about what a block contains as well, if it is a chest or storage block, it will display that knowledge. If it is an RF-based machine, it will display the items inside, RF Storage, and the RF/t usage. If it a liquid storage block, known as a tank, it will display how many buckets of that liquid you have in the block.
Collect some cobble and make some tools. Tools to make tools that make tools . . .

It's time to put the mine in Minecraft. Now get you pickaxe, you're going mining!

Don't forget, OreExcavate is in this pack (you can mine all of one block that is touching... until you run out of durability on your tool)
The Nether holds some items that aren't available anywhere else, just like Vanilla. Get yourself a portal and jump in! While you're there, pick up some blaze rods. (You'll need them later!)

Sometimes when we give you a reward for completing a quest, you'll see that there is a 'Choice Reward'. This means that you need to click one of the items to receive before clicking 'Claim'. Then you'll get your item that you selected.
Sugar... Yum. Get some sugarcane, get more sugarcane! Win-Win.

In Vanilla, this marks just about the end of the game. In modded, this is just the beginning.

§oGood luck

Food is super important in Minecraft. Food is even more important when you use OreExcavator - the mod that lets you hold a key (Grave --> ~ by default) to mine lots of one resource at once. When you mine like this you get hungry.
The Nether Provides a vast array of resources that are not available in the overworld. How about you go gather some of them?
In addition to providing a much more reliable source of Ender Pearls, the End now also contains Ender Biotite Ore, an equivalent of Nether Quartz, added by the mod Quark.
No Description
No Description

This chisel, from the mod Chisel, not to be confused with Chisel and Bits, changes the texture of over 125 blocks to variants of itself. It can make stone look like stone bricks, magma turn blue, and so much more. Either right click the air to open a menu or right click a block in-game to see what variants there are.

If you've ever thought that Minecraft blocks were too big, not the right size or shape, or just ugly, you can fix it now. This chisel can tear down a single block into 64 'bits'. You can then use the bits to make new blocks, walls, stairs, or even spheres!
Storage is a concept that becomes even more important in Modded Minecraft, as there is a much wider variety of items to store. This Quest Branch will cover the various options available for storage.

This section is all about food. Food can be super important in Modded Minecraft because some task use your hunger meter. For example, in this pack you can use OreExcavator, which allows you to break lots of one type of block at once. When it does this, though, you use a your hunger meter much faster. It's a great way to quickly clear an area while just requiring food.

This upgraded chest, crafted with a chest and 8 iron ingots, can hold 54 stacks (as much as a double chest) in only a one block space. It can also be placed between double chests, allowing for much more compact storage.

Just like your typical ender chest, you can break it, carry it, and put it back down. This ender chest has a bonus feature of different color combination channels. §cRed-Red-Red§r can hold all your red colored items, while §e§6Yellow-Yellow-Yellow§r can hold your sunflowers (for example).

Use any dye and right-click the top buttons to change the color (it consumes the dye).

'Cooking For Blockheads' is a mod designed to assist you with cooking food with the ingredients you have on hand. When you have these items touching, you can use them to create wild combinations of fantastical foods.
This chest has 81 slots, 1.5 times more than that of a double chest. It is crafted with 8 gold ingots and an iron chest.
This Chest can hold 108 slots of items, the most of any chest available in this modpack. That is, it can hold twice the items of a double chest or iron chest.

betterquesting:10.name:8: A Slope? Is this still Minecraft?
betterquesting:10.desc:8: No Description
These blocks from Chisel are great for building and chiseling with. 42
§rThese are some interesting variants of Chisel's blocks. See if you chisel them!

This tank is perfect for liquid transportation. It acts like an ender chest for fluids. It also can have different color combinations on the top, so §cred-red-red §rcould be for molten iron and §9blue-blue-blue §rcould be water.

§r§rUse any dye and right-click the top buttons to change the color (it consumes the dye).

Just like the ender chest you just finished completing, this has different channels too! But this is a backpack, which means you don't have to place it, open it, and break it. Just right click while it's in your hand and it opens!

To set the colors of the pouch, first dye your ender chest. Then Shift+right click with the pouch on your chest and it will change to that color combo. . . that's what their wiki says anyways.
This chest can hold just as much as the Diamond Chest, but also has the advantage of being Blast-Resistant, so those pesky creepers cannot damage it at all.
This chest, which holds 108 slots just like the diamond chest, allows you to view what is contained inside, without even opening it! Pretty cool, huh?

Sometimes there are things in mods that you don't really get, but you really want.

Like a cow in a jar.

Just why?

But hey, it produces milk!

All you need is a cow, a milk jar... and an anvil (how else did you think you were going to get that huge cow in there!?)

Lots of food from Pam's Harvest requires special tools for cooking things. This is a list of the tools that you can use to get bigger and better food items.

§oYum!

It's like a crafting table 2.0, but it's a station. It crafts and can see the last inventory to touch it. It also connects to some other tables in a tabbed GUI. More on those tables later...

(For this reward, first click either the Banana Bread or the Pumpkin bread and then click 'Claim'. You only get one)

One bonus of using the Tinker's smeltery is the increased metal amount per ore. If you put an iron ore in a furnace, it produces 1 ingot. With the smeltery, it will create 2 ingots worth of molten iron. Then you can put it into an ingot mold, or 9 ingots worth into a basin for a block of iron.

Each type of item that is used to create a tool in Tinkers' has a different property, and they have different properties when used as different parts of the tool. Some will assist you, like the naturally slow repairing of wood. Others are annoying, like the cheapskate property of stone which causes less durability when it is used as the head. See §oMaterials and You§r for more info.

One that has to be mentioned is LivingWood from Botania (a magic mod). It has regeneration and additional modifiers, which allows for adding extras to your tool, like redstone for speed, lapis for luck, quartz for sharpness, and even a mending moss that works like vanilla's mending but stores extra XP when possible.

These are some of the extras that can be used to beef up your tools.

§oThis quest won't be possible until you've completed at least some of the magic quest line.

§rYou'll need some enderium, manyullyn and miron.

Enderium is formed in the smeltery with ender pearls and casted into ingots.

Manyullyn is alloyed from cobalt and ardite, two metals found in the nether.

Mirion is alloyed from terrasteel, manasteel, elementium, cobalt, and glass. You should have some cobalt from the last quest, but you'll need to open an elven portal to get elementium.
The part builder allows you to use your stencils and some material to create a part of a tool. See §oMaterials and You§r for a full list of part materials.

Sorry, you can't draw here.

This special table lets you change the stencils into different tool part stencils. Take these stencils and put them in the part builder to make parts of tools. It takes between 2 to 4 parts to create a tool (in the tool station).
Build this to be able to put your tools together!
These are used to create all sorts of tools in Tinkers' Smeltery. For now, make a few to get started. It's just planks and sticks, nbd.
All those pesky patterns are going to get annoying quickly. This handy chest will hold them for you and be seen if it touches the other tables. Just don't try put anything else in there.

The basis of a Tinkers' Smeltery, Groot is a tree-like creature from Guardians . . .

Rather, grout is crafted with sand and gravel. When it is baked it forms seared bricks.

Alternatively, you can smelt cobblestone in a smeltery and pour it an ingot cast to get seared bricks. This helps a lot when you're short on clay, sand, or gravel!

These are parts of a smeltery.

Controler: Right click to view contents. Insert and melt items from here

Bricks: forms the exterior of the smeltery

Drain: Allows fluids to inserted/removed from the smeltery

Basin: Fills up with fluids that cool and become blocks

Table: Fills with fluids to form tool parts, ingots, and more

Faucet: Allows you to click on it to remove fluids from the smeltery if there is a table/basin underneath it.

Tank: When it contains lava, the smeltery can melt items and use a little lava in the process. Eventually, you can use other hot fluids to melt items.


Check the Tinkers' guidebook - §nMaterials and YOU§r - for more info!
It does everything a tool station does, but it can create even more tools. Need mob heads? There's a tool for that! Want to farm and attack with the same tool? There's a another tool for that!

It does exactly what you might expect: pulverizes things.

The pulverizer can be used an ore doubler in combination with a furnace. For example, pulverizing iron ore will give you 2 pulverized iron. Smelting the pulverized iron will give you an ingot.

Pulverized items can be used for other thing too, though. Like hardened glass. Pulverizing wool gives you string back, concrete turns back into powder, the list goes on and on and on.

This machine uses energy to melt items into fluids.

It even makes lava. Ooooh, ahhhh.
The Quartz grindstone is a manual grinder. After building it, you'll need to attach a wooden crank to the top of the machine. Press and hold your right mouse button to start grinding.

Machine and device frames are the basis of Thermal Expansion.

Machines are made with a machine frame and use energy (called RF) to manipulate items and fluids.

Devices are made with device frames and manipulate items and fluids without energy.
This machine gives extra wood products when it takes them apart. 1 log = 6 planks!?!?

Isn't farming boring? Do you wish a machine would do it for you?

Now it does. This machine takes Phyto-gro, your favorite plant, sunlight, and RF.

Before you move on to Part II, you'll need some sort of power. Power in modded takes on a few forms. Some can be converted from one to another, and some mods require their own generator to work. If you're ever in doubt of what type of power is needed, Google it.

Each of these energy types has a way to transfer power between blocks. These have different names, but basically work like plugging the machine in. Connect your cord to the energy generator and make a line to the block to power.

§lPro/lazy tip:§r If you don't know what power type is needed for a block, try a few different conduits/cords/ducts until you find the one that attaches to your block. Then power your conduit/cord/duct and you're good to go

Power transfer in this pack is mainly through fluxducts. Early game, the easiest of these to create is the leadstone fluxduct. You need redstone, glass, and lead ingots. They don't transfer power very quickly, but they'll let you get to the next level.

You'll need to create some power before you use it or transfer it. Start small. This coal generator produces about 185 RF/tick.

It takes some iron, cobblestone, coal, and a piece of black quartz (You can get these from mining black quartz ore)
The hardened fluxduct transfers power much faster. Upgrade your leadstone fluxducts to hardened fluxducts with some invar and a bit more redstone. Now you have some power!

Once you get farther into your world, you'll find yourself needing to move MORE power. Unfortunatly, your hardened fluxducts are upgraded to the max. Now you'll need to make a redstone fluxduct.

First, create an empty redstone energy fluxduct (2 electrum ingots and a hardened glass).
Then fill it in the fluid transposer with redstone. You'll be set on power... for a little while.

Still not enough power? Good news, you can upgrade your redstone energy fluxducts!

You'll need some redstone and signalum. See if you can find the JEI recipie to alloy it in the smeltery.

Alternatively, you can upgrade an empty redstone energy fluxduct to an empty signalum fluxduct then fill it with molten redstone in the fluid transposer.

Super powered!

Upgrade you signalum fluxducts with more redstone and some enderium, or upgrade you empty ones and then fill these.

The end. There is nothing better. Literally infinite power transfer. This should be illegal.

You'll need to upgrade your resonant fluxducts (filled only) to create an empty cryo-stabalized flucduct and then fill it with some gelid cryotheum. Good fun!

When canola is pressed, fermented, and put into an oil generator, it creates power. You'll need to jumpstart the process with some power, but eventually it will be strong enough to power itself and quite a bit more.

Like a lot of other mods, this has its own resources that need to be collected. Certus quartz has three forms: regular, charged, and pure. Regular and charged are found naturally in the world, while pure has to be grown.

Charged certus quartz ore is found semi-rarely in the world, but it's visible in the dark.


§nNote§r: Charged certus quartz's primary purpose in life is the creation of fluix. Please help it fulfill it's destiny. Regular certus quartz can be substituted in every other recipie.

Charged crystals can be created from regular certus quartz in a charger.

For production, you'll need an energy acceptor (if you're using RF), some ME Glass cables, and the charger. All of these require fluix crystals.

Fluix crystals are created by tossing a redstone dust, nether quartz, and a charged crystal into water. Wait a moment and they will transform... just don't ask why red, light blue, and white make a dark purple crystal. IT'S SCIENCE PEOPLE!

The inscriber is the basis of AE2. To use it, however, you'll need to go hunting. You need to find the 4 presses. These allow the inscriber to press gold, silicon, diamonds, and certus quartz crystals into different mechanical parts.

To get these presses, you need to wander the surface and look for large areas of earth that have been blown away by large astroids of Sky Stone. To break the sky stone, you'll need at least a diamond pickaxe. (I hope you made a decent pick from Tinkers'!)


§§§rA note from your friend: §r§oYou should make the slime sling and slime boots. Trust me, they help in long distance travel!
No Description

Botania is a floral mod, but don't be tricked, these flowers can be nastly little buggers. With explosions, food, and magic, there's something for everyone!


For some mods, the authors will create an in-game explanation, often contained in a book. For Botania, this is incredibly helpful.



§a§o§r§oPick up your copy of Lexica Botania today!
You shouldn't look here for help. Look at your new book, it has the recipe in there!

Time to get your flower power on!


Seriously, that's a lot of flowers

A simple recipe, just stone and a petal in the right shape.

Note that there is no GUI, and you don't right click to place items in. You actually throw (default Q) items into it. Finish each recipe with some seeds.
Don't look here for help, go look at your brand-spanking-new book!

You have a dark feeling. You need someone's will.


Throw this item at a dying monster. When you see white particles, finish them off to gain their will.

Those wills weren't enough. You feel the need for more. There must be a better way.

Let's get a hellfire forge, and ramp up some production of wills.

To start, put a will (of at least 1.0 point value) into your Hellfire forge in the far right slot. In the corner slots, you'll need lapis, redstone, gold ingots, and glass.




§r§oI hear they taste like Tartar! Mmm!

betterquesting:10.name:8: One Sword to Kill them All
betterquesting:10.desc:8:
The whole will collecting process is becoming quite bothersome. Let's ramp things up a bit.

Put a Petty Tartaric Gem and an iron sword into a Hellfire Furnace to get a Sentient sword. It's so sentient that this sword will convice the other wills to join forces with it in a spectacular bout of wit.

Or more simply, it always gets wills from mobs you kill with it, and stores them for you.

§oIt is unfortunately, your §o§o§cblood§r§o. Smeared all over that thing. Don't worry though, it won't hurt... too much.

§rThe recipe isn't that bad though. A few gold ingots, some stone, a furnace, and a demonic will. Whip it up in no time.



We won't go into how here, but this is a multi-block structure that can be upgraded to unlock further and more powerful recipes. To do this, you will need a 23w x 23l x 9h room and an internet connection. Search something like "minecraft blood altar" in your favorite search engine (Google).  Be SURE to include minecraft in that search!

§oOr a bit more, the name is confusing me.

§rSometimes a petty thing just isn't enough. This is like a bigger will wallet. (Mine's for bills, but whatever floats your boat)

§oMore! More! More!

§rWhen a lesser really is lesser...
I think the title says it all.

§oFinally, I can have them! All of them! They all belong to me!

§rI don't even know what you want this for. Can you seriously get this many?

It will hold a large amount of your mana for you. It is also used for other things, like the creation of mana pearls and manasteel ingots.

It's kind of like a battery, but with mana instead of electricity.

A great starter to mana production, the endoflame burns dropped fuel that is within its reach. A block of coal will last longer than a piece, but be wary because each item only lasts so long. After the equivelent of 288 items being smelted in a furnace, the fuel is consumed.

A magical flower that turns adjacent (including diagonal) stone and wood into their living varieties.

Craft it with 4 white petals and water in the apothecary.

The mana spreader is, I think anyways, the most important part of Botania as well as the most frustrating.

Mana spreaders move mana. That's all.

Say you have an endoflame that is producing mana. You also have a mana pool a few blocks away. You need that mana in that pool, but mana is magic; you can't just pick it up. To move the mana, put a mana spreader next to the endoflame. Then shift-R-click on the spreader with a wand of the forest and shift-R-click on the pool. When the spreader works, you'll see a green particle effect jumping between the spreader and the object it is filling.
A great all around tool for Botania. It can reorient mana spreaders, connect mana sources and destinations, and looks fantastic as you skip through flower fields.

§o§oThis is the stuff Groot is made of

§rJust like livingrock, livingwood is another Botania item that is used for crafting magical items. Much like wood, it can be turned into planks and sticks as well.
The pure daisy has a special power. Any stone surrounding it will be turned into livingrock after a little while. The livingrock is used in crafting magical items in Botania
No Description
Manasteel is created by throwing iron ingots into a mana pool. The iron ingot and some mana will be consumed, but it's worth it. We think.

§o§l§o§o§r§l§nThe Ultimate Botanic Metal: Terrasteel

§r§oIt's so difficult, it takes two quests!

§rSo to set this up, you'll need to arrange these blocks in a 3x3 checker board pattern with the Agglomeration plate on top of the central block of living stone. Then collect all the mana you can, cause this takes a ton of mana (about half a pool per ingot).

Canola you say?

Yup, that oil that your mom cooks comes from a plant. Gather some of it, but we won't be using it for cooking.

Now that you have the setup, just toss a mana pearl, mana diamond, and manasteel ingot onto the plate and wait...

...



...


Just a few more minutes and you should have this cooked up... Really.

Yup, you'll need to toss some diamonds (into a §mlava§r§r§r §r§rmana pool).

It's kinda fun isn't it? Oh, just fun for me? 


                     >:)

if you like to keep things quiet, this flower will help you out. it absorbs sounds that are created in a small radius around it, and converts this into mana. the mana, however, is so insignificant that it can't be transfered or used.


§o[no letters were yelled in the making of this quest]

§oAlternately, 'You Shall Not Pass!', but that's overused.

§rThis flower gives all other mobs (non-player) a slow effect when they are in a short radius of the flower.

This mana generating flower eats leaves that grow around it. It produces a large amount of mana as well. Be careful though, because it likes to eat non-stop. If it stops eating, it stops for minutes at a time.

§oThis plant likes to EAT!

§rThis one (I wont' try to pronounce it) likes to eat food. It's a bit picky though. It likes to eat food it hasn't eaten lately, so keep a wide variety around.

Once fed, this plant will start generating mana.

So you have an anvil, a milk jar, and your cow ready to go... now what?

Get your cow on top of your milk jar (and lock it in!) Place your anvil so that it smashes that poor cow into your jar. 


§oViola! Cow in a jar!

Welcome to ADG Omicron XII!! This quest book is meant to serve as a tutorial for those who may be new to Modded Minecraft. This chapter covers things you may already know, but also introduces the utility mods JEI and The One Probe, and the content mod Quark.
Now that you understand the bare minimum of modded Minecraft, let's start by introducing some mods that expand upon basic vanilla concepts, such as food, building, and storage.

This chapter is based on technological and industrial mods. We will introduce "Low-Tech" mods such as Immersive Engineering and Tinkers' Construct, as well as Actually Additions as a gateway to higher-tech items. See Part II for "High-Tech" mods.
Now that you've learned some "low-tech" mods, we will introduce some "High-tech" mods such as Thermal Expansion, NuclearCraft, Industrial Foregoing, and AE2.

You may think that after the last two chapters modded Minecraft is all technology. However, this is simply not the case. Magic exists too, in mods such as Blood Magic, and it combines with tech in mods like Embers and Botania. So get out there, and become a Master Archmage!!
Another Tech Chapter? Yes, this chapter showcases mods such as Environmental Tech, RFTools, and XNet that would not fit in the second Tech chapter.
